   "source": [
    "# Introduction to PyTorch: Tensors and Gradient Descent"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "803d45b8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This tutorial provides an introduction to PyTorch tensors, automatic differentiation, and optimization with gradient descent.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Introduction to Tensors\n",
    "\n",
    "Tensors are matrices, similar to numpy arrays, with the added benefit that they can be used to calculate gradients (more on that later). MPoL is built on PyTorch, and uses a form of gradient descent optimization to find the \"best\" image given a dataset and choice of regularizers.\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll start this tutorial by importing the torch and numpy packages. Make sure you have [PyTorch installed](https://pytorch.org/get-started/locally/) before proceeding."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "9cc207f8",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:57.994662Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:57.994371Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.862486Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.861371Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import torch"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "77263f8a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are several [ways to initialize a tensor](https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/tensors.html). A common method to create a tensor is from a numpy array:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "58771fb5",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.867378Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.866911Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.878402Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.877250Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "tensor([[1, 2],\n",
      "        [3, 4]])\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "an_array = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]])\n",
    "a_tensor = torch.tensor(an_array)  # creates tensor of same size as an_array\n",
    "\n",
    "print(a_tensor)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7280768e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Tensors are similar to numpy arrays---many of the same [operations](https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/torch.html) that we would perform on numpy arrays can easily be performed on PyTorch tensors. For example, we can compare how to calculate a matrix product using numpy and PyTorch"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "ba5ee9fb",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.882173Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.881898Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.889464Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.888597Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Numpy array multiplication result: [[21 24  7]\n",
      " [47 54 21]]\n",
      "Torch tensor multiplication result: tensor([[21, 24,  7],\n",
      "        [47, 54, 21]])\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "another_array = np.array([[5, 6, 7], [8, 9, 0]])  # create 2x3 array\n",
    "another_tensor = torch.tensor(\n",
    "    another_array\n",
    ")  # create another tensor of same size as above array\n",
    "\n",
    "# numpy array multiplication\n",
    "prod_array = np.matmul(an_array, another_array)\n",
    "\n",
    "# torch tensor multiplication\n",
    "prod_tensor = torch.matmul(a_tensor, another_tensor)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Numpy array multiplication result: {prod_array}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Torch tensor multiplication result: {prod_tensor}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "55aa9fd1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Calculating Gradients"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b581bac1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "PyTorch provides a key functionality---the ability to calculate the gradients on tensors. Let's start by creating a tensor with a single value. Here we are setting ``requires_grad = True``, we'll see why this is important in a moment."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "bfb1a102",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.894688Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.894374Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.904880Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.904032Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "tensor(3., requires_grad=True)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x = torch.tensor(3.0, requires_grad=True)\n",
    "x"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4457cf97",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's define some variable $y$ in terms of $x$:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "c27a3592",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.908543Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.908159Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.912486Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.911568Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "y = x ** 2"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "942f8902",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    " We see that the value of $y$ is as we expect---nothing too strange here."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "652a43e7",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.915826Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.915561Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.919994Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.919294Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "x: 3.0\n",
      "y: 9.0\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(f\"x: {x}\")\n",
    "print(f\"y: {y}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ee0f16e9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "But what if we wanted to calculate the gradient of $y$ with respect to $x$? Using calculus, we find that the answer is $\\frac{dy}{dx} = 2x$. The derivative evaluated at $x = 3$ is $6$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The magic is that can use PyTorch to get the same answer---no analytic derivative needed!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "44aeacc0",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.923743Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.923345Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.930013Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.929225Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "tensor(6.)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "y.backward()  # populates gradient (.grad) attributes of y with respect to all of its independent variables\n",
    "x.grad  # returns the grad attribute (the gradient) of y with respect to x"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9488ebc2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "PyTorch uses the concept of automatic differentiation to calculate the derivative. Instead of computing the derivative as we would by hand, the program is using a computational graph and mechanistic application of the chain rule. For example, a computational graph with several operations on $x$ resulting in a final output $y$ will use the chain rule to compute the differential associated with each operation and multiply these differentials together to get the derivative of $y$ with respect to $x$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "661e4a7b",
   "metadata": {
    "lines_to_next_cell": 2
   },
   "source": [
    "## Optimizing a Function with Gradient Descent\n",
    "\n",
    "If we were on the side of a hill in the dark and we wanted to get down to the bottom of a valley, how would we do it?\n",
    "\n",
    "We wouldn't be able to see all the way to the bottom of the valley, but we could feel which way is down based on the incline of where we are standing. We would take steps in the downward direction and we'd know when to stop when the ground felt flat.\n",
    "\n",
    "Before we leap, though, we need to consider how large our steps should be. If we take very small steps, it will take us a longer time than if we take larger steps. However, if we take large leaps, we might completely miss the flat part of the valley, and jump straight across to the other side of the valley.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can look at the gradient descent from a more mathematical lense by looking at the graph $y = x^2$:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "ab049358",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.933712Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.933344Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.937066Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.936239Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def y(x):\n",
    "    return torch.square(x)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b3795f5d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We will choose some arbitrary place to start on the left side of the hill and use PyTorch to calculate the tangent.\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that Matplotlib requires numpy arrays instead of PyTorch tensors, so in the following code you might see the occasional ``detach().numpy()`` or ``.item()`` calls, which are used to convert PyTorch tensors to numpy arrays and scalar values, respectively. When it comes time to use MPoL for RML imaging, or any large production run, we'll try to keep the calculations native to PyTorch tensors as long as possible, to avoid the overhead of converting types."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "69d87a40",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.942050Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:58.941548Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.240612Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.239675Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 480x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 459,
       "width": 459
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x = torch.linspace(-5, 5, 100)\n",
    "plt.plot(x, y(x))\n",
    "\n",
    "x_start = torch.tensor(\n",
    "    -4.0, requires_grad=True\n",
    ")  # tensor with x coordinate of starting point\n",
    "y_start = y(x_start)  # tensor with y coordinate of starting point\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(x_start.item(), y_start.item())  # plot starting point\n",
    "\n",
    "# we can calculate the derivative of y = x ** 2 evaluated at x_start\n",
    "y_start.backward()  # populate x_start.grad\n",
    "slope_start = x_start.grad\n",
    "\n",
    "# and use this to evaluate the tangent line\n",
    "tangent_line = slope_start * (x - x_start) + y_start\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.plot(x, tangent_line.detach().numpy())\n",
    "plt.xlabel(r\"$x$\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(r\"$y$\")\n",
    "plt.xlim(xmin=-5, xmax=5)\n",
    "plt.ylim(ymin=0, ymax=25)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "145467af",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see we need to go to the right to go down toward the minimum. For a multivariate function, the gradient will point in the direction of the steepest downward slope. When we take steps, we find the x coordinate of our new location by this equation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$x_{new} = x_{current} - \\nabla y(x_{current}) * (step \\: size)$\n",
    "\n",
    "where:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $x_{current}$ is our current x value\n",
    "\n",
    "- $\\nabla y(x_{current})$ is the gradient at our current point\n",
    "\n",
    "- $(step \\: size)$ is a value we choose that scales our steps\n",
    "\n",
    "We will choose ``step_size = 0.1``:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "f3c3e087",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.244582Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.244289Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.460436Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.459518Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 480x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 459,
       "width": 459
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x = torch.linspace(-5, 5, 100)\n",
    "plt.plot(x, y(x), zorder=0)  # plot y = x ** 2\n",
    "\n",
    "step_size = 0.1\n",
    "\n",
    "# Tensors containing current coordinates at the starting point we chose:\n",
    "x_current = x_start\n",
    "y_current = y(x_current)\n",
    "\n",
    "# To keep track of our coordinates at each step, we will create 2 lists, initialized with the values at our chosen starting point\n",
    "# These lists will be used to plot points with Matplotlib.pyplot so we use .item() to only retain the value in the tensor\n",
    "x_coords = [x_current.item()]\n",
    "y_coords = [y_current.item()]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Slope at current point\n",
    "y_current.backward()  # populate x_current.grad\n",
    "slope_current = (\n",
    "    x_current.grad\n",
    ")  # tensor containing derivative of y = x ** 2 evaluated at current point\n",
    "\n",
    "# Using equation for x_new to get x coordinate of second point, store it in a tensor\n",
    "# We cannot use torch.tensor(...) to make a new tensor from previous tensors without altering the\n",
    "# computational graph. We use .item() to only use float values to create our new tensor\n",
    "x_new = torch.tensor(\n",
    "    x_current.item() - (slope_current.item()) * step_size, requires_grad=True\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plug in x_new into y = x ** 2 to get y_new of second point\n",
    "y_new = y(x_new)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Store second point coordinates in our lists\n",
    "x_coords.append(x_new.item())\n",
    "y_coords.append(y_new.item())\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(x_coords, y_coords)  # plot points showing steps\n",
    "# replot the last point in a new color\n",
    "plt.scatter(x_coords[-1], y_coords[-1], c=\"C1\", zorder=1)\n",
    "plt.text(-2, 5, \"step 1\", va=\"center\")\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xlim(xmin=-5, xmax=5)\n",
    "plt.ylim(ymin=-1, ymax=25)\n",
    "plt.xlabel(r\"$x$\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(r\"$y$\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6b380d47",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The gradient at our new point (shown in orange) is still not close to zero, meaning we haven't reached the minimum. We continue this process of checking if the gradient is nearly zero, and taking a step in the direction of steepest descent until we reach the bottom of the valley. We'll say we've reached the bottom of the valley when the absolute value of the gradient is $<0.1$:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "1197e649",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.464949Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.464542Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.676026Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.674878Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 480x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 459,
       "width": 459
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x = torch.linspace(-5, 5, 100)\n",
    "plt.plot(x, y(x), zorder=0)  # plot y = x ** 2\n",
    "\n",
    "# We are now at our second point so we need to update our tensors containing our current coordinates\n",
    "x_current = x_new\n",
    "y_current = y_new\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# We automate this process with the following while loop\n",
    "y_current.backward()  # populate x_current.grad\n",
    "while abs(x_current.grad) >= 0.1:  # Check to see if we're at minimum\n",
    "    # Get tensors containing new coordinates\n",
    "    x_new = torch.tensor(\n",
    "        x_current.item() - x_current.grad.item() * step_size, requires_grad=True\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    y_new = y(x_new)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Add new coordinates to lists\n",
    "    x_coords.append(x_new.item())\n",
    "    y_coords.append(y_new.item())\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Update current position\n",
    "    x_current = x_new\n",
    "    y_current = y_new\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Update current slope\n",
    "    y_current.backward()  # populate x_current.grad\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(x_coords, y_coords)  # plot points showing steps\n",
    "plt.scatter(x_coords[-1], y_coords[-1], c=\"C1\")  # highlight last point\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xlim(xmin=-5, xmax=5)\n",
    "plt.ylim(ymin=-1, ymax=25)\n",
    "plt.xlabel(r\"$x$\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(r\"$y$\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a0d9b20d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This works, but it takes a long time since we have several small steps.\n",
    "\n",
    "Can we speed up the process by taking large steps? Most likely, yes. But there is a danger in taking step sizes that are too large. For example, let's repeat this exercise with a step size of $1.5$. Our first step now looks like:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "d7b4057b",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.680406Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.679858Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.914299Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-08T18:57:59.913207Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {

   "source": [
    "x_large_step = torch.linspace(-20, 20, 1000)\n",
    "plt.plot(x_large_step, y(x_large_step), zorder=0)  # plot y = x ** 2\n",
    "\n",
    "# Current values at starting point we chose:\n",
    "x_large_step_current = torch.tensor(-4.0, requires_grad=True)\n",
    "y_large_step_current = y(x_large_step_current)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Slope at current point\n",
    "y_large_step_current.backward()  # populate x_large_step_current.grad\n",
    "slope_large_step_current = (\n",
    "    x_large_step_current.grad\n",
    ")  # tensor containing derivative of y = x ** 2 evaluated at current point\n",
    "\n",
    "# To keep track of our coordinates at each step, we will create 2 lists, initialized with the coordinates at our chosen starting point\n",
    "# These lists will be used to plot points with Matplotlib.pyplot so we use .item() to only retain the value in the tensor\n",
    "x_large_coords = [x_large_step_current.item()]\n",
    "y_large_coords = [y_large_step_current.item()]\n",
    "\n",
    "# New step_size\n",
    "large_step_size = 1.5\n",
    "\n",
    "# Get coordinates of our second point using x_new equation and y = x ** 2\n",
    "x_large_step_new = torch.tensor(\n",
    "    x_large_step_current.item() - slope_large_step_current.item() * large_step_size,\n",
    "    requires_grad=True,\n",
    ")\n",
    "y_large_step_new = y(x_large_step_new)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Store second point coordinates in our lists\n",
    "x_large_coords.append(x_large_step_new.item())\n",
    "y_large_coords.append(y_large_step_new.item())\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(x_large_coords, y_large_coords)  # plot points showing steps\n",
    "plt.scatter(x_large_coords[-1], y_large_coords[-1], c=\"C1\")\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xlim(xmin=-20, xmax=20)\n",
    "plt.ylim(ymin=-1, ymax=260)\n",
    "plt.xlabel(r\"$x$\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(r\"$y$\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

   "source": [
    "*Note the change in scale.* With only one step, we already see that we stepped *right over* the minimum to somewhere far up the other side of the valley (orange point)! This is not good. If we kept iterating with the same learning rate, we'd find that the optimization process diverges and the step sizes start blowing up. This is why it is important to pick the proper step size by setting the learning rate appropriately. Steps that are too small take a long time while steps that are too large render the optimization process invalid. In this case, a reasonable choice appears to be ``step size = 0.6``, which would have reached pretty close to the minimum after only 3 steps.\n",
    "\n",
    "To sum up, optimizing a function with gradient descent consists of\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Calculate the gradient at your current point\n",
    "2. Determine if the gradient is within the stopping criterion (in this case, the gradient is about equal to zero or $<0.1$), if so stop\n",
    "3. Otherwise, take a step in the direction of the gradient and go to #1\n",
    "\n",
    "Autodifferentiation frameworks like PyTorch allow us to easily calculate the gradient of complex functions, including a large set of prior/regularizer functions that we would want to use for Regularized Maximum Likelihood (RML) imaging. This makes it relatively easy to quickly and efficiently solve for the \"optimal\" image given a set of data and regularizer terms.\n",
